    \"UnityEditor.ShaderGraph.Vector1MaterialSlot\",\n    \"m_ObjectId\": \"c83c609069d44ffcabf6b3bd4d64825f\",\n   
    \"m_Id\": 2,\n    \"m_DisplayName\": \"G\",\n    \"m_SlotType\": 1,\n    \"m_Hidden\":
    false,\n    \"m_ShaderOutputName\": \"G\",\n    \"m_StageCapability\": 3,\n   
    \"m_Value\": 0.0,\n    \"m_DefaultValue\": 0.0,\n    \"m_Labels\": []\n}\n\n{\n   
    \"m_SGVersion\": 0,\n    \"m_Type\": \"UnityEditor.ShaderGraph.StickyNoteData\",\n   
    \"m_ObjectId\": \"cb56fbae305241889d87f596d1aae55d\",\n    \"m_Title\": \"4.
    Noise + UV -> Height map\",\n    \"m_Content\": \"We want to achieve a Height
    map defining the dunes in our material. \\nTo make our material more versatile,
    we add Tiling support: create a Tiling and Offset node, and a new Vector 2 parameter
    UV Tiling which we will feed into the Tiling pin of the new node. Now, take the
    tiled UV coordinates and sum with the outputs of Step 1 and 3.\\nTake the result
    of this operation and feed it through a Fraction node, which will return the
    decimal part. \\nFinally, create a Custom Function node: we will use a code function
    in the Shader Graph, because we need a feature which isn't supported natively
    by ShaderGraph. Select your Custom Function node and find the Graph Inspector
    on the right. Here, ensure that the Type option is set to File: then, write \\\"PolygonGradient\\\"
    for Name and find the Shading file in the Source asset box. Lastly, create 4
    inputs and 1 output: in order, these need to have the following names and types:\\n\\r\\nUV
    - Vector 2\\r\\nSides - Float\\r\\nWidth - Float\\r\\nHeight - Float\\r\\n\\r\\nOut
    - Float\",\n    \"m_TextSize\": 0,\n    \"m_Theme\": 0,\n    \"m_Position\":
    {\n        \"serializedVersion\": \"2\",\n        \"x\": -2449.0,\n        \"y\":
    1145.0,\n        \"width\": 822.0,\n        \"height\": 239.0\n    },\n    \"m_Group\":
    {\n        \"m_Id\": \"\"\n    }\n}\n\n{\n    \"m_SGVersion\": 0,\n    \"m_Type\":
